🛡️ The Kubernetes "Ghost in the Machine": Deep-Dive CRI-O Troubleshooting

As an Infrastructure Lead, you eventually stop fearing Error states and start fearing Running states that lie. This guide contains real-world, high-stakes scenarios where kubectl is useless and only the crictl scalpel can save the cluster.
🏗️ Scenario 1: The Infinite Terminating Pod (The "Ghost" Sandbox)

The Context: A high-frequency trading app in a BFSI environment. We triggered a deployment, but the old pods are stuck in Terminating for 4 hours. No amount of kubectl delete pod --force is working.
🕵️ The Investigation

When kubectl can't kill a pod, it’s usually because the Kubelet is waiting for the CRI (Container Runtime Interface) to confirm the Sandbox (Pause Container) is dead. If the runtime loses track, the pod becomes a "Ghost."
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Simulate the Hang: Kill the sandbox directly at the CRI-O level without telling Kubernetes.
     

# Get the Sandbox ID
SB_ID=$(sudo crictl pods --name <pod-name> -q)

# Force stop the infrastructure container
sudo crictl stopp $SB_ID

The Crisis: Run kubectl delete pod <pod-name>. It hangs indefinitely because the Kubelet is retrying a delete operation on a handle that is already corrupted in the runtime.

The Deep Fix: Bypass the API and purge the runtime's memory.
 

    # Verify the 'NotReady' or 'Exited' state in CRI-O
    sudo crictl inspectp $SB_ID | jq .status.state

    # Manually purge the sandbox
    sudo crictl rmp $SB_ID

The Lesson: The "Pause" container is the anchor. If the anchor is stuck in the mud, the ship (Pod) cannot move.
🧟 Scenario 2: The PID 1 Silent Killer (Zombie Exhaustion)

The Context: A node suddenly stops accepting new pods. kubectl describe node shows Ready, but logs say Resource temporarily unavailable.
🕵️ The Investigation

In Linux, every process needs a PID. If a container spawns thousands of child processes (like a poorly written shell script or a Java leak) and the Pause container (which acts as PID 1 for the Pod) can't reap them, the node hits its pid_max limit.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Generate the Leak:
     

kubectl run leak-test --image=busybox -- /bin/sh -c "while true; do sleep 1000 & done"

Find the Root PID on the Host:
 

# Map the container to the Host OS Process ID
CONT_ID=$(sudo crictl ps --name leak-test -q)
HOST_PID=$(sudo crictl inspect $CONT_ID | jq .info.pid)

The Deep Dive: Use pstree to see the zombie children branching off the runtime's process.
 

pstree -p $HOST_PID

The Resolution: Use crictl to kill the process group that kubectl can't reach.
 

    sudo crictl stop $CONT_ID

🗝️ Scenario 3: The Secret Snatcher (Node-Level Privilege Escalation)

The Context: You have a disgruntled intern with sudo access to a worker node but no ClusterAdmin permissions. Can they steal the production DB credentials? Yes.
🕵️ The Investigation

Kubernetes Secrets are "secure" in the API, but they are injected as plain text into the container's environment or filesystems at the runtime level.
🛠️ The Replication (The "Audit")

    The Target: A pod running with an environment variable DB_PASSWORD.

    The Extraction: No Kubeconfig required.
     

    # List all running containers on the node
    sudo crictl ps

    # Inspect the container's spec directly from the CRI-O socket
    sudo crictl inspect <container-id> | jq '.info.runtimeSpec.process.env'

    The Result: The password appears in the terminal.
    The Lesson: Security is a multi-layered onion. RBAC protects the API; sudo policies and encryption-at-rest protect the Node.

❄️ Scenario 4: The Uninterruptible Sleep (Storage Hang)

The Context: A Pod is Running but kubectl exec and kubectl logs hang forever.
🕵️ The Investigation

The process is in State D (Uninterruptible Sleep). This usually happens when a network-attached volume (NFS/iSCSI) goes offline. The kernel is waiting for I/O, and it will not allow the process to be killed—even by kill -9.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Check the State:
     

PID=$(sudo crictl inspect <id> | jq .info.pid)
ps -q $PID -o state,comm

If output is D, your storage is the culprit.

Find the Source:
 

    sudo crictl inspect <id> | jq '.info.runtimeSpec.mounts'

    The Fix: You must fix the mount on the Host, not the container. Once the host mount is recovered or lazily unmounted (umount -l), the crictl commands will start responding again.
🏗️ Scenario 5: The "No-Space" Paradox (Leaked Log Handles)

The Context: df -h shows the disk is 100% full on /var/log, but when you run du -sh *, you can't find the large files. You delete old logs, but the disk space is not reclaimed.
🕵️ The Investigation

When a container is writing logs and you delete the log file manually from the host, the file descriptor remains open in the container runtime. The space is not freed until the process is killed.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Find the Offender:
     

# Look for 'deleted' files still held by processes
sudo lsof +L1 | grep crio

Verify via crictl: Find which container owns that PID.
 

TARGET_PID=<PID_from_lsof>
sudo crictl ps -q | xargs sudo crictl inspect | jq -r "select(.info.pid == $TARGET_PID) | .status.metadata.name"

The Fix: Don't just delete files; restart the container via CRI to release the handle.
 

    sudo crictl stop <container-id>

🏗️ Scenario 6: The "Pre-Stop" Trap (Graceful Shutdown Failure)

The Context: You updated a deployment, but the new pods aren't starting because the old ones are "Terminating" and holding onto a unique shared resource (like a hardware lock or a fixed port).
🕵️ The Investigation

The preStop hook or the application's SIGTERM handler is deadlocked. Kubernetes will wait for terminationGracePeriodSeconds (default 30s) before a SIGKILL, but sometimes even that fails if the runtime-to-kernel communication is lagged.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    The Deep Check: See if the process is actually receiving the signal.
     

sudo crictl inspect <id> | jq .status.state

The Manual Intervention: Talk directly to the process via the host PID.
 

HPID=$(sudo crictl inspect <id> | jq .info.pid)
sudo kill -9 $HPID

The Cleanup: If the container still shows in crictl ps, force remove it:
 

    sudo crictl rm -f <id>

🏗️ Scenario 7: The Image Overlay Corruption

The Context: A pod fails to start with OCI runtime create failed or failed to mount overlay. This often happens after a hard power failure or a storage driver crash.
🕵️ The Investigation

The local image layer on the node is corrupted. kubectl will keep retrying and failing.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Identify the Layer: Check the logs of the runtime.
     

journalctl -u crio | grep "storage-driver"

The Nuclear Option (Node-Specific): You need to wipe the local cache of that image.
 

    # Find the image ID
    IMG_ID=$(sudo crictl images | grep <image-name> | awk '{print $3}')
    # Force remove the image (and all its layers)
    sudo crictl rmi $IMG_ID

    The Recovery: kubectl delete pod will now force a fresh, uncorrupted pull from the registry.

🏗️ Scenario 8: The "Identity Crisis" (MAC Address Conflicts)

The Context: Two pods on the same node cannot talk to each other, but they can talk to pods on other nodes.
🕵️ The Investigation

In extremely rare cases, or when using custom CNI configurations, two Pause Containers (Sandboxes) might end up with conflicting virtual interface metadata in the CRI cache.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Inspect the Sandbox Network:
     

# Check the network config for both pods
sudo crictl inspectp <id-1> | jq .info.runtimeSpec.linux.namespaces
sudo crictl inspectp <id-2> | jq .info.runtimeSpec.linux.namespaces

Enter the Namespace: Use nsenter to check the actual ARP table inside the Pause container.
 

    NET_NS=$(sudo crictl inspectp <id-1> | jq -r '.info.runtimeSpec.linux.namespaces[] | select(.type=="network") | .path')
    sudo nsenter --net=$NET_NS ip neigh

    The Fix: Flush the ARP cache or recreate the Sandbox via crictl rmp.

🏗️ Scenario 9: The "Slow-Death" (Resource Leak in Runtime)

The Context: Over months, the memory usage on the node grows (Node Memory Leak), but top shows no single process using it.
🕵️ The Investigation

The CRI runtime itself or the shim (conmon/runc) might be leaking memory due to excessive exec or logs calls from monitoring tools.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Stat Analysis:
     

# Check stats for all containers including hidden ones
sudo crictl stats -a

Correlate with Systemd:
 

    systemd-cgtop

    If the crio.service slice is ballooning, the runtime needs a restart. In production, you must drain the node first: kubectl drain <node>.

🏗️ Scenario 10: The Time-Warp (Clock Skew)

The Context: Your banking app is rejecting transactions with "Token Expired" even though the token was just generated.
🕵️ The Investigation

The Node's hardware clock has drifted, and the container, which shares the UTS namespace and clock with the host (usually), is out of sync.
🛠️ The Replication & Fix

    Compare Node vs Container:
     

date # Host Time
sudo crictl exec <id> date # Container Time

The "Host-Path" Trap: If they differ, check if the container has a specific /etc/localtime mounted via hostPath.
 

    sudo crictl inspect <id> | jq '.info.runtimeSpec.mounts[] | select(.destination=="/etc/localtime")'

    The Fix: Fix the chronyd or ntp service on the host. The container will instantly reflect the change because it shares the kernel clock.

